4. They characterize Silenus, as one that was alwaies drunk;
                        Silenus's being filled with wine, from Gen. 49. 12. as 'tis ſuppoſed from what followes Gen. 49. 12. His eyes ſhall be red with wine: which Solomon makes the character of one overcome with wine, Prov. 23. 29, 30. to whom rednes of eyes, &c. 5. They aſcribe to Silenus for his meat, Cows Milk: which Bochart
                        Silenus's meat Cows milk, from Gen. 49. 12. makes to be traduced from Gen. 49. 12. and his teeth white with Milk. Whence he concludes thus: The Devil could have imagined nothing more abominable whereby to profane the moſt holy miſteries of our Religion, and to expoſe it to the cavils of moſt wicked men, &c.

2. As for Minerva; Voſsius (de Idololatr. lib. 1. cap. 17.)2. Minerva. makes her to be the ſame with Naamah, Tubalcains ſiſter, Gen. 4. 22. Her name 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
Stephanus makes to be Phenician;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 : which Bochart derives from 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 to move war; whence the Oncean Gates at Thebes. The fable of Minerva her being borne out of Jupiters head, they generally refer to the generation of Chriſt, the Divine wiſdome.
